	<td class="alt1">
	
		
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div><br /> &lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;Quote:&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;hr&gt;It is a fairly common attack by someone without a legitimate argument to try to discredit the person who said something in some way when they cannot actually discredit their statement. Davy wasn't a highly educated man but he was wise in a common sense sort of way, and this story I thought was a great way to illustrate the way our government works now and why its so wrong and such a mess.[/quote]<br />
<br />
Had you simply made an argument about &quot;how our government works,&quot; then there would be no person to discredit. But since you felt the need to bring up Davey Crockett as a person worth quoting, it's fair to see whether that is the case. As far as I can tell, from what few facts are available about Crockett's life, he was just another run-of-the-mill politician. He introduced no lasting legislation, was not a particularly notable orator and did not write anything particularly noteworthy. Crockett accomplished nothing more than any other two-term Congressman in history, but he happened to be the beneficiary of the Whig Party's myth makers. There is no reason to take Crockett any more seriously than anyone else -- in fact, given the baloney surrounding his life (much of it coming from the man himself), there's a good deal of reason to regard Crockett as nothing more than a joke.<br />
<br />
Having said that, his argument in this particular case is fundamentally flawed, because it assumes that government has no right to give charity. Of course it does, as long as it serves the general welfare -- and that's exactly how several of the Constitutional Framers intended it.<br />
<br />
&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;Quote:&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;hr&gt;People do wrong things for the right reasons, out of the goodness of their heart and ignorance. That doesn't make them any more right.[/quote]<br />
<br />
I agree.  <br /></div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		
		
	
	</td>
